  "prompt": "What are the best books/Tutorials to learn C# for non-beginners programmers?",
  "response": "Here are some recommended books and resources for intermediate to advanced C# programmers:\n\nBooks:\n1. \"C# in Depth\" by Jon Skeet\n- Highly detailed exploration of C# language features\n- Great for understanding advanced language concepts\n\n2. \"Pro C# 9 with .NET 5\" by Andrew Troelsen\n- Comprehensive guide to modern C# and .NET\n- Covers advanced topics and best practices\n\n3. \"Effective C#\" by Bill Wagner\n- Focuses on idiomatic C# and best practices\n- Provides practical advice for writing better code\n\n4. \"CLR via C#\" by Jeffrey Richter\n- Deep dive into .NET runtime and internal mechanics\n- Advanced understanding of .NET architecture\n\nOnline Tutorials/Courses:\n1. Microsoft's official documentation\n- Comprehensive and up-to-date\n- Free resource with in-depth explanations\n\n2. PluralSight C# courses\n- Advanced video tutorials\n- Covers various advanced topics\n\n3. YouTube channels:\n- IAmTimCorey\n- Nick Chapsas\n- Milan Jovanovi\u0107\n\nOnline Platforms:\n1. Udemy advanced C# courses\n2. Coursera .NET specializations\n3. edX .NET programming courses\n\nRecommended Websites:\n1. docs.microsoft.com\n2. stackoverflow.com\n3. dotnetcurry.com\n\nAdditional Resources:\n- GitHub open-source projects\n- Technical blogs\n- Conference talks",
